Schedule Renovate updates once weekly

We already have GitHub's vulnerability scanning enabled for this
repository, which will alert us about vulnerabilities in NPM packages we
use. Everything else can be updated with less urgency.

https://help.github.com/articles/about-security-alerts-for-vulnerable-dependencies/

Fix #69: Provide multiple dataset endpoints

Before this commit, we served one giant JSON blob for each dataset. For
example, /datasets/user-activity included all user activity data for all
metrics in all categories.

With this change, each dataset now has multiple endpoints. Each endpoint
serves a portion of the data. For example, /datasets/user-activity lists
all category and metric names. /datasets/user-activity/Russia/YAU serves
only the YAU data in the Russia category.

This should allow us to improve the performance of the Ensemble
front-end. For example, this will allow us to fix the issue of the
Hardware dashboard taking about 5 seconds to load even on a good
connection.

I already have a commit to Ensemble with the necessary changes which
will be published soon.

Set NODE_ENV environment variable automatically

The NODE_ENV environment variable must be set to "production" when the
Docker container is being built for production use, but apparently
Heroku ignores any environment variables set through their UI when
building Docker containers.

* eslint

Pass audit even if some modules require updates

The audit is intended to notify developers about any modules with
security vulnerabilities. Most can be updated, but some cannot. When
there are modules that cannot be updated, there's really not much that
can be done about it, so we don't want to fail the whole "npm test"
command as a result.
Replace nsp with "npm audit", fix errors

Recommend npm, not yarn, for running tests
Update testing instructions in README

Run linting with npm test

I've gone back and forth about this a bunch of times, but I've come to
think this is the best approach. It's true that linting isn't exactly
the same as testing, but most people just run "npm test" and I wouldn't
want them to miss out on our linting results.

The "validate" script remains as an alias of "test" in case anyone is
using that out of habit.
